[[File:Mastodon mascot vector version.svg|alt=A cartoon Mastodon mascot|thumb|The mascot of the Mastodon social network — a [[mastodon]]]]
'''Mastodon''' is [[free and open-source software]] for running [[Self-hosting (web services)|self-hosted]] [[social networking service]]s.{{Efn|Mastodon itself is not a social network, but merely one of the multiple software implementations of the ActivityPub protocol. In common usage however, it is referred as a social network.}} It has [[microblogging]] features similar to [[Twitter]], which are offered by a large number of independently run [[Node (networking)|nodes]], known as [[Instance (computer science)|instances]], each with its own [[code of conduct]], [[terms of service]], [[privacy policy]], privacy options, and [[content moderation]] policies.<ref name="Chan 2022">{{cite news |last=Chan |first=Wilfred |title=Mastodon gained 70,000 users after Musk's Twitter takeover. I joined them |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2022/nov/01/mastodon-twitter-elon-musk-takeover |access-date=3 November 2022 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=2 November 2022}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite news |last=Farokhmanesh |first=Megan|date=7 April 2017 |title=A beginner's guide to Mastodon, the hot new open-source Twitter clone |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/4/7/15183128/mastodon-open-source-twitter-clone-how-to-use|access-date=4 February 2021 |work=[[The Verge]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Wong |first=Joon Ian |title=How to use Mastodon, the Twitter alternative that's becoming super popular |url=https://qz.com/951078/the-complete-guide-to-using-mastodon-the-twitter-twtr-alternative/|access-date= 4 February 2021 |work=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]] |date=6 April 2017 |language=en}}</ref>

Each user is a member of a specific Mastodon instance (also called a server), which can interoperate as a [[federated social network]], allowing users on different instances to interact with each other. This is intended to give users the flexibility to select a node whose policies they prefer, but keep access to a larger social network. Mastodon is also part of the [[Fediverse]] ensemble of computer servers, which use shared protocols allowing users to interact with other users on computers running compatible software packages<ref>{{cite web|url=https://activitypub.rocks/news/mastodon-ap-and-new-cr.html|title=Mastodon launches their ActivityPub support, and a new CR!|website=ActivityPub.rocks|access-date=20 January 2019}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=February 2023}} such as [[PeerTube]] and [[Friendica]]. Mastodon is [[crowdfunded]] and does not contain ads.

Mastodon was created by [[Eugen Rochko]] and announced on [[Hacker News]] in October 2016,<ref>{{cite web |date=2016-10-05 |title=Show HN: A new decentralized microblogging platform |url=https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=12646083 |access-date=2022-10-31}}</ref> and [[#2022 Twitter-related spikes in adoption|gained significant adoption in 2022]] in the wake of [[Acquisition of Twitter by Elon Musk|Twitter's acquisition by Elon Musk]].<ref name=":3" />{{Unreliable source?|date=February 2023}}<ref name=MSN1/><ref name=CNET1/>

The project is maintained by German [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit]] Mastodon [[gGmbH]].<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Knight|first=Will|title=The Man Behind Mastodon Built It for This Moment|language=en-US|magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|url=https://www.wired.com/story/the-man-behind-mastodon-eugen-rochko-built-it-for-this-moment/|access-date=2023-03-05|issn=1059-1028}}</ref>

==Functionality and features==
Mastodon servers run social networking software that is capable of communicating using [[World Wide Web Consortium|W3C]]'s [[ActivityPub]] standard, which has been implemented since version 1.6.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/mastodon/mastodon/releases/tag/v1.6.0|title=Release 1.6.0|website=github.com}}</ref> A Mastodon user can therefore interact with users on any other server in the [[Fediverse]] that supports ActivityPub.

Since version 2.9.0 Mastodon has offered a single column mode for new users by default.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.joinmastodon.org/2019/06/mastodon-2.9/|title=Mastodon 2.9|website=Official Mastodon Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2023}} In advanced mode Mastodon approximates the microblogging user experience of [[TweetDeck]]. Users post short-form status messages, historically known as "toots", for others to see. On a standard Mastodon instance, these messages can include up to 500 text-based characters, greater than Twitter's 280 character limit,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/9/26/16363912/twitter-character-limit-increase-280-test|title=Twitter just doubled the character limit for tweets to 280|website=Theverge.com|access-date=3 December 2018|date=26 September 2017}}</ref>{{Irrelevant citation|reason=The source never mentions the article topic|date=February 2023}}<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|title=How To Get Started on Mastodon and Leave Twitter Behind|url=https://www.pcmag.com/how-to/how-to-get-started-on-mastodon-and-leave-twitter-behind|access-date=2021-02-04|website=PCMAG|language=en}}</ref> although numerous Mastodon servers have [[fork (software development)|forked]] the source code to allow a larger character limit.

Users join a specific Mastodon server, rather than a single centralized website or application. The servers are connected as nodes in a network, and each server can administrate its own rules, account privileges, and whether to share messages to and from other servers. Many servers have a theme based on a specific interest. It is also common for servers to be based around a particular locality, region, or country.<ref name="The Verge: beginner" /><ref>{{Cite web|title=Ditt lokale sosiale nettverk — oslo.town|url=https://oslo.town/about|access-date=2020-10-19|website=Mastodon hosted on oslo.town|language=en}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2023}}<ref>{{Cite web|title=Tŵt Cymru {{!}} Toot Wales|url=https://toot.wales/about|access-date=2020-10-19|website=Mastodon hosted on toot.wales|language=en}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2023}}

Mastodon includes a number of specific privacy features. Each message has a variety of privacy options available, and users can choose whether the message is public or private. Public messages display on a global feed, known as a timeline, and private messages are only shared on the timelines of the user's followers. Messages can also be marked as unlisted from timelines or direct between users. Users can also mark their accounts as completely private. In the timeline, messages can display with an optional [[content warning]] feature, which requires readers to click on the hidden main body of the message to reveal it. Mastodon servers have used this feature to hide [[spoiler (media)|spoilers]], [[trigger warning]]s, and [[not safe for work|not safe for work (NSFW)]] content, though some accounts use the feature to hide links and thoughts others might not want to read.<ref name=":1" /><ref name="The Verge: beginner" />

Mastodon aggregates messages in local and federated timelines in real-time. The local timeline shows messages from users on a singular server, while the federated timeline shows messages across all participating Mastodon servers. Users can communicate across connected Mastodon servers with usernames similar in format to full email addresses.<ref name=":2" /><ref name="The Verge: beginner"/>

=== Content moderation ===
In early 2017, journalists like [[Sarah Jeong]]<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|date=2017-04-04|title=Mastodon Is Like Twitter Without Nazis, So Why Are We Not Using It?|work=Motherboard|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/783akg/mastodon-is-like-twitter-without-nazis-so-why-are-we-not-using-it|access-date=2018-09-21}}</ref> distinguished Mastodon from Twitter for its approach to combatting harassment.<ref name="The Verge: beginner" /> Mastodon uses community-based moderation, in which each server can limit or filter out undesirable types of content, while Twitter uses a single, global policy on [[content moderation]]. For example, mastodon.social and several other servers ban content that is illegal in Germany or France, including [[Neo-Nazism|Nazi symbolism]], [[Holocaust denial]], and [[Antisemitism in 21st-century Germany|incitement of violence against Jews]]. Other instances of Mastodon, however can choose to take a more lenient approach to such material. Servers can also choose to limit or filter out messages with disparaging content. The main author of the Mastodon software, [[Eugen Rochko]], believes that small, closely related communities deal with unwanted behaviour more effectively than a large company's small safety team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/we-distribute/one-mammoth-of-a-job-an-interview-with-eugen-rochko-of-mastodon-23b159d6796a|title=One Mammoth of a Job: An Interview with Eugen Rochko of Mastodon|website=medium.com/we-distribute|date=9 July 2018|access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=February 2023}} Users can also block and report others to administrators, much like on Twitter.<ref name="The Verge: beginner" /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rochko |first1=Eugen |title=Learning from Twitter's mistakes |url=https://medium.com/tootsuite/learning-from-twitters-mistakes-c272d67bba76 |website=Medium.com |access-date=7 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181210074855/https://medium.com/tootsuite/learning-from-twitters-mistakes-c272d67bba76 |archive-date=10 December 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=February 2023}}

Administrators of servers can block other servers from interacting with their own, an action called "defederation". Administrators and users rely on the "#fediblock" hashtag—created by users @artistmarciax and @gingerrroot—to alert others to troublesome servers.{{Citation needed|date=January 2023}}

=== Comparison to Twitter ===
Unlike Twitter, Mastodon is privacy-focused and only searches [[hashtag]]s and ''mentioned'' accounts in the Fediverse, not the full text of toots. Some servers support searching the full text of the user's own toots.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.joinmastodon.org/admin/optional/elasticsearch/|title=Full-text search|website=Mastodon documentation site|accessdate=27 December 2022}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2023}}<ref name="osint">{{cite web|url=https://www.secjuice.com/mastodon-osint-a-comprehensive-introduction/|title=Mastodon OSINT: A Comprehensive Introduction|last=Hassan|first=Nihad|date=27 November 2022|accessdate=27 December 2022|website=Secjuice}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=February 2023}} Furthermore, searching for toots will only show results from the Mastodon instance the user is on and from parts of the Fediverse that that instance has cached via federation, not from all toots on all instances.

For similar reasons, only hashtags can appear in a Mastodon instance's trending topics, not arbitrary popular words, and trending topics vary between instances, since individual instances are aware of different subsets of toots from the whole Fediverse.{{citation needed|date=December 2022}}

===Versions===
In September 2018, with the release of version 2.5 with redesigned public profile pages, Mastodon marked its 100th release.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.joinmastodon.org/2018/09/mastodon-2.5-released|title=Mastodon 2.5 released: Highlights from the changelog|website=blog.joinmastodon.org|access-date=3 December 2018}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2023}}{{So?|date=February 2023}} Mastodon 2.6 was released in October 2018, introducing the possibilities of verified profiles and live, in-stream link previews for images and videos.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.joinmastodon.org/2018/10/mastodon-2.6-released|title=Mastodon 2.6 released: Highlights from the changelog|website=Blog.joinmastodon.org|access-date=3 December 2018}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2023}}{{So?|date=February 2023}} Version 2.7, in January 2019, made it possible to search for multiple hashtags at once, instead of searching for just a single hashtag. Version 2.7 has more robust moderation capabilities for server administrators and moderators, while accessibility, such as contrast for users with sight issues, was improved.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.joinmastodon.org/2019/01/mastodon-2.7|title=Mastodon 2.7 released: Highlights from the changelog|website=Blog.joinmastodon.org|access-date=20 January 2019}}</ref> The ability for users to create and vote in polls, as well as a new invitation system to manage registrations was integrated in April 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.joinmastodon.org/2019/04/mastodon-2.8|title=Mastodon 2.8 Highlights from the changelog|website=blog.joinmastodon.org|access-date=11 April 2019}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2023}}{{So?|date=February 2023}} Mastodon 2.8.1, released in May 2019, made images with content warnings blurred instead of completely hidden.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.joinmastodon.org/2019/05/improving-support-for-adult-content-on-mastodon|title=Improving support for adult content on Mastodon|website=blog.joinmastodon.org|access-date=6 May 2019}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2023}}{{So?|date=February 2023}} In version 2.9 in June 2019, an optional single-column view was added.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.joinmastodon.org/2019/06/mastodon-2.9|title=Introducing the single-column layout|website=blog.joinmastodon.org|access-date=15 July 2019}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2023}}{{So?|date=February 2023}} This view became the default displayed to new users, with a user "preferences" option to switch to a multiple-column-based view.{{Citation needed|date=September 2022}}

In August 2020, Mastodon 3.2 was released. It included a redesigned audio player with custom thumbnails and the ability to add personal notes to one's profile.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Mastodon 3.2|url=http://blog.joinmastodon.org/2020/08/mastodon-3.2/|access-date=2020-08-21|website=Official Mastodon Blog|language=en}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2023}}{{So?|date=February 2023}}

In July 2021, an official client for [[iOS]] devices was released. According to the project's leadership,{{who|date=December 2022}} the release was part of an effort to attract new users.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2021/7/30/22602275/mastodon-decentralized-social-network-official-ios-app-launches |title=Mastodon now has an official iPhone app |website=The Verge |date=30 July 2021 |access-date=31 July 2021}}</ref>

Mastodon 4.0 was released in November 2022, including language support for translating posts, editing posts and following hashtags.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Release v4.0.0 · mastodon/mastodon |url=https://github.com/mastodon/mastodon/releases/tag/v4.0.0 |access-date=2022-11-20 |website=GitHub |language=en}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2023}}{{So?|date=February 2023}}

==Software==
{{Expand section|with=more details on technical information|date=November 2018}}
Mastodon is written as [[free and open-source software]] (FOSS) for [[Federated social network|federated]] microblogging, which anybody can contribute code to, and which anyone can run on their own server infrastructure, if they wish, or join servers run by other people<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fediverse.network/mastodon|title=Mastodon Instances — The Fediverse Network|access-date=3 December 2018|archive-date=12 November 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201112031908/https://fediverse.network/mastodon|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2023}} within the [[fediverse]] network.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hackernoon.com/welcome-to-mastodon-111d9227e56a|title=Welcome to Mastodon|first=Eugen|last=Rochko|date=1 April 2017|website=Hacker Noon|access-date=3 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180912080249/https://hackernoon.com/welcome-to-mastodon-111d9227e56a|archive-date=12 September 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2023}} Its [[Front and back ends|server-side software]] is powered by [[Ruby on Rails]] and [[Node.js]], and its front end is written in [[React.js]] and [[Redux (JavaScript library)|Redux]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.joinmastodon.org/administration/installation/|title=Installation|access-date=26 December 2018|website=joinmastodon.org|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227084921/https://docs.joinmastodon.org/administration/installation/|archive-date=27 December 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2023}} The [[database]] software is [[PostgreSQL]].<ref>{{Citation|title=tootsuite/mastodon|date=2021-02-04|url=https://github.com/tootsuite/mastodon|publisher=Mastodon|access-date=2021-02-04}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2023}} The service is interoperable with the [[decentralized application|decentralized]] social networks and platforms which use the [[ActivityPub]] protocol between each other.<ref name="activitypub">{{cite web|url=https://github.com/tootsuite/mastodon/releases/tag/v1.6.0 |title=Release v1.6.0 |website=GitHub|access-date=2017-09-20}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2023}} Since version 3.0, Mastodon dropped previous support for [[OStatus]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Your self-hosted, globally interconnected microblogging community: tootsuite/mastodon|date=2019-10-04|url=https://github.com/tootsuite/mastodon/releases/tag/v3.0.0|publisher=TootSuite|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2023}}

Client apps for interacting with the Mastodon API are available for desktop computer operating systems, including [[Windows (operating system)|Windows]], [[macOS]] and the [[Linux|GNU/Linux]] family of operating systems, and on [[mobile phone]] systems, including [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[List of open-source mobile phones|open-source mobile phones]].<ref name=":2" /><ref name="apps">{{cite web|url=https://joinmastodon.org/apps |title=List of apps |website=joinmastodon.org|access-date=2022-02-12|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220127104448/https://joinmastodon.org/apps|archive-date=27 January 2022}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2023}}

==Adoption==
[[File:What is Mastodon.webm|thumb|Introductory video explaining Mastodon]]
While Mastodon was first released in October 2016, the service began to expand in late March and early April 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://au.pcmag.com/social-networking/47343/feature/what-is-mastodon-and-will-it-kill-twitter|title=What Is Mastodon and Will It Kill Twitter?|date=2017-04-06|website=PCMag Australia|first=Chandra|last=Steele}}</ref>  Servers were mostly operated by academic institutions, journalists, hobbyists, and activists.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Klemmens |first=Ben |date=2023-01-02 |title=Mastodon—and the pros and cons of moving beyond Big Tech gatekeepers |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2023/01/mastodon-highlights-pros-and-cons-of-moving-beyond-big-tech-gatekeepers/ |access-date=2023-01-18 |website=Ars Technica |language=en-us}}</ref> ''[[The Verge]]'' wrote that the community at this time was small and that it had yet to attract the personalities that keep users at Twitter.<ref name="The Verge: beginner"/> The global use had risen from 766,500 users as of 1 August 2017, to 1 million users on 1 December 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mnm.eliotberriot.com/dashboard/db/network-drilldown?refresh=30m&amp;orgId=1&orgId=1&from=now-7d&to=now |title= dynamic status of mastodon|website=Eliotberriott.com|access-date= 16 April 2017}}{{dead link|date=October 2019}}</ref><ref name="dec2017onemil">{{cite news|title=Mastodon Users (bot), December 1, 2017, 4:00 PM|url=https://lou.lt/@mastodonusercount/99099871022836220|newspaper=Loultstodon|date=December 2017 |access-date=1 December 2017}}</ref> In{{Nbsp}}November 2017 artists, writers, and entrepreneurs such as [[Chuck Wendig]], [[John Scalzi]], [[Melanie Gillman]] and later John O'Nolan joined in.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Bonnington |first=Christina |url=http://www.dailydot.com/debug/mastodon-open-source-social-media/ |title=Mastodon is an open source, decentralized version of Twitter |work=[[The Daily Dot]] |date=2016-11-22 |access-date=2017-01-11 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Tidey |first=Jimmy |url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/en/what-would-twitter-be-with-wikipedia-politics/ |title=What would Twitter be if it adopted Wikipedia's politics? |work=[[openDemocracy]] |date=2017-01-06 |access-date=2017-01-11 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chronicle.com/blogs/profhacker/are-you-on-mastodon-yet-social-network-of-our-own/63261|title=Are You on Mastodon Yet? Social Network of Our Own – ProfHacker - Blogs - The Chronicle of Higher Education|website=Chronicle.com|access-date=2018-09-21|date=28 November 2016}}</ref>

Another spike in popularity came in March through April 2018, due to the concerns about user privacy raised by the ''#deletefacebook'' effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/business/facebook-deletefacebook-mastodon-zuckerberg-cambridge-analytica-20180323.html|title=Facebook's poor care of customer data is driving users to social networks such as Mastodon|first=Brian|last=Fung|agency=Washington Post|website=www.philly.com}}</ref>

Some "[[alt-tech]]" groups are using Mastodon including some that are ideologically neutral as well as political extremists and [[organized retail crime]] groups.<ref>Neil Spencer (2021) Alt-Tech Social Networks: What Investigators and Analysts Need to Know-->{{cite Q|Q115117517}}</ref>

Membership of Mastodon and other alternative social media sites increased in early December 2018<ref>{{cite web |title=User Count Bot |url=https://mastodon.social/@usercount |website=Mastodon.social |access-date=2018-12-03}}</ref>{{Better source needed|date=December 2022|reason=Should have a secondary source.}} after [[Tumblr]] announced its intention to ban all adult content from the site.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gibson |first1=Kate |title=Tumblr banning adult content starting Dec. 17, citing porn concerns |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/tumblr-banning-adult-content-starting-dec-17-citing-porn-concerns/ |access-date=3 December 2018 |work=CBS News |date=3 December 2018}}</ref>

In November 2019, nearly 20,000 Twitter users in India temporarily shifted to Mastodon over complaints by users against Twitter's moderation policies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/india/1746734/angry-twitter-india-users-are-migrating-to-mastodon-in-thousands/|title=This chart from Mastodon's creator shows just how angry some Indian Twitter users are|last=Kapur|first=Manavi|website=Quartz India|date=12 November 2019 |language=en|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref>

To circumvent the increasing online censorship of social networks in mainland China, an increasing number of Chinese language users have chosen to migrate to Mastodon in 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-china-tightens-controls-on-social-media-some-users-seek-refuge-under-the-radar-11659551841|title=As China Tightens Controls on Social Media, Some Users Seek Refuge Under the Radar|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=2022-08-04|first=Lu|last=Shen}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.scmp.com/tech/tech-trends/article/3192843/chinese-social-media-users-are-flocking-decentralised-mastodon|title= Chinese social media users are flocking to the decentralised Mastodon platform to find community amid crackdown at home|work=SCMP|date=2022-09-18}}</ref>

===2022 Twitter-related spikes in adoption===
{{see also|December 15, 2022 Twitter suspensions}}
A spike in Mastodon's user participation occurred in April 2022, following the 25{{nbsp}}April announcement of [[Acquisition of Twitter by Elon Musk|Elon Musk purchasing Twitter]]. By 27{{nbsp}}April, {{val|30000|fmt=commas}} new users had joined Mastodon.<ref name="Engadget_after_Musks_Twitter_takeover" /><ref name="OKOpress_Musk_bought_Twitter" /> On 28{{nbsp}}April 2022, the [[European Data Protection Supervisor]] (EDPS) launched the official ActivityPub microblogging platform (called EU{{nbsp}}Voice) of the EU institutions, bodies and agencies (EUIs), based on Mastodon.<ref>''[https://edps.europa.eu/press-publications/press-news/press-releases/2022/edps-launches-pilot-phase-two-social-media_en EDPS launches pilot phase of two social media platforms]'' (press release).</ref>

Musk's acquisition became final on 27{{nbsp}}October 2022. Mastodon had an increase of {{val|70,000|fmt=commas}} new users from a resultant "[[diaspora]]" on 28 October alone.<ref name="chan-2022">{{cite news|last1=Chan|first1=Wilfred|title=Mastodon gained 70,000 users after Musk's Twitter takeover. I joined them|date=2 November 2022|work=The Guardian|location=London, United Kingdom|issn=0261-3077|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2022/nov/01/mastodon-twitter-elon-musk-takeover|access-date = 2022-11-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Twitter: 70,000 users join rival Mastodon after Musk takeover |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/technology/twitter-70000-users-join-rival-mastodon-after-musk-takeover/ar-AA13CEYX |access-date=2022-11-12 |website=MSN |language=en-US}}</ref> Daily downloads increased substantially, rising from 3,400 daily downloads on 27 October to 113,400 on 6 November 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Fischer |first=Sara |date=2022-11-08 |title=Musk's Twitter chaos opens door for challengers |url=https://www.axios.com/2022/11/08/twitter-challengers-rise-musk-chaos |access-date=2022-11-09 |website=Axios |language=en}}</ref> According to Rochko, by 3 November, use of the federated network had grown to 665,000 active users, with a few growing pains. In particular, Mastodon's largest instance, mastodon.social, needed capacity upgrades to handle the new load.<ref name=":3">{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2022/11/03/decentralized-social-network-mastodon-grows-to-655k-users-in-wake-of-elon-musks-twitter-takeover/|title=Decentralized social network Mastodon grows to 655K users in wake of Elon Musk's Twitter takeover|first=Sarah|last=Perez|date=3 November 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Metz |first=Rachel |date=2022-11-05 |title=With Twitter in chaos, Mastodon is on fire {{!}} CNN Business |url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/11/05/tech/mastodon/index.html |access-date=2022-11-15 |website=CNN |language=en}}</ref> Accounts on a server called journa.host founded by [[Adam Davidson (journalist)|Adam Davidson]] are restricted to professional journalists.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2022/11/21/style/mastodon-twitter-adam-davidson.html Chaos on Twitter Leads a Group of Journalists to Start an Alternative]</ref>

Mastodon's increased adoption continued in the days following the Twitter takeover. On 11 November, the number of new users of the platform compared to the previous week was reported to be 700,000,<ref name=MSN1>{{Cite web |title=How to Join Mastodon? Be Patient and Kind |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/technology/how-to-join-mastodon-be-patient-and-kind/ar-AA13Xmg1 |access-date=2022-11-12 |website=MSN |language=en-US}}</ref> moving Mastodon over the 7 million user mark.<ref name=CNET1>{{cite web | url=https://www.cnet.com/tech/services-and-software/twitter-in-turmoil-heres-how-to-join-the-mastodon-social-network/ | title=Confused by Twitter 'Replacement' Mastodon? Here's How to Get Started | website=CNET}}</ref> During that period, several prominent figures joined Mastodon, including prominent actors, comedians, journalists, political activists, and politicians.<ref>{{Cite web |title=15+ Famous Celebrities On Mastodon 2022! |date= 24 November 2022 |url= https://deasilex.com/celebrities-on-mastodon/ |access-date=2022-12-02 |language=en-US}}</ref> In December 2022, the number of monthly active users of Mastodon reached two million.<ref>{{cite web |title=Servers |url=https://joinmastodon.org/servers |publisher=Mastodon |access-date=16 December 2022}}</ref>

On 15 December, the official Mastodon Twitter account was banned from Twitter, [[December 15, 2022 Twitter suspensions|as well as other accounts with links to some Mastodon instances]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Taylor |first=Hatmaker |date=16 December 2022 |title=Twitter suspends Mastodon's account and bans links to Mastodon servers |url=https://techcrunch.com/2022/12/15/elon-musk-suspends-mastodon-twitter-account-over-elonjet-tracking/?guccounter=1 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221216100905/https://techcrunch.com/web/20221216100905/https://techcrunch.com/2022/12/15/elon-musk-suspends-mastodon-twitter-account-over-elonjet-tracking/ |archive-date=16 December 2022 |website=TechCrunch}}</ref> On the following day, Twitter began to flag all Mastodon links as malware, preventing Twitter users from sharing them.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-63999452 Twitter blocks users from sharing Mastodon links] [[BBC News]]</ref><ref>[https://www.cnn.com/2022/12/16/tech/mastodon-twitter-links/index.html Elon Musk's Twitter blocked links to rival Mastodon. That could raise alarms among regulators] [[CNN]]</ref> Media coverage of the bannings included an erroneous report of an account for "John Mastodon" (a misspelling of ''@joinmastodon'') being banned, described as "founder of a competing social media company named after himself".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Schorr |first=Isaac |date=2022-12-16 |title=Hypocrisy and Fear All the Way Down at Twitter |work=Mediaite |url=https://www.mediaite.com/opinion/hypocrisy-and-fear-all-the-way-down-at-twitter/ |access-date=2022-12-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221216232836/https://www.mediaite.com/opinion/hypocrisy-and-fear-all-the-way-down-at-twitter/ |archive-date=2022-12-16}}</ref> Mastodon users wrote fictional backstories and memes about "John Mastodon" and circulated the [[hashtag]] #JohnMastodon.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Frauenfelder |first=Mark |date=2022-12-18 |title=Mastodon users embrace columnist's funny error about a fictitious "John Mastodon" |url=https://boingboing.net/2022/12/18/mastodon-users-embrace-columnists-funny-error-about-a-fictitious-john-mastodon.html |access-date=2022-12-18 |website=Boing Boing |language=en-US}}</ref>

Following the Mastodon suspension and ban on Mastodon links on Twitter,<ref>[https://www.theverge.com/2022/12/15/23512113/twitter-blocking-mastodon-links-elon-musk-elonjet Twitter is blocking links to Mastodon], [[The Verge]]</ref> Twitter introduced a new policy on 18 December to prohibit sharing links on Twitter to a variety of social media websites, with Mastodon being one of those blocked. The policy stated that it prohibited links in both tweets and account details and that accounts that violated the policy would be suspended.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2022/12/18/business/twitter-ban-social-media-competitors-mastodon.html Twitter to Ban Accounts That Promote Rival Social Media], ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/twitter-policy-idCAKBN2T20CH Elon Musk launches poll asking if he should quit as Twitter CEO], [[Reuters]]</ref><ref>[https://www.theverge.com/2022/12/18/23515221/twitter-bans-links-instagram-mastodon-competitors Twitter abruptly bans all links to Instagram, Mastodon, and other competitors] The Verge</ref> By 19 December, the policy and official mentions about it had been removed from Twitter web pages.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2022/12/18/twitter-bans-links-facebook-instagram-mastodon-accounts/10921759002 Twitter deletes new policy banning 'free promotion' of rival social media platforms], ''[[USA Today]]''</ref><ref>[https://gizmodo.com/elon-musk-twitter-external-links-mastodon-1849909896 Twitter Suddenly Reverses Course on 'Policy' That Banned Links to Competing Social Media Sites], [[Gizmodo]]</ref> Musk stated the following day that banning users for posting Mastodon links had been a mistake.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/tech/elon-musk-delete-mastodon-twitter-b2249096.html Elon Musk says taking down accounts for posting links of rival Mastodon was 'a mistake'], ''[[The Independent]]''</ref>

Rochko claimed that at least five [[venture capital]] firms looking to invest in Mastodon had been turned away by December 2022, and that Mastodon's nonprofit status would not be jeopardized.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Times |first=Financial |date=2022-12-28 |title=Twitter rival Mastodon rejects funding to preserve nonprofit status |url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2022/12/twitter-rival-mastodon-rejects-funding-to-preserve-nonprofit-status/ |website=Ars Technica |language=en-us}}</ref>

By the start of January 2023, Mastodon had 1.8 million active users, down 30% from its peak of over 2.5 million active users in early December 2022.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nicholas |first1=Josh |title=Elon Musk drove more than a million people to Mastodon – but many aren't sticking around |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2023/jan/08/elon-musk-drove-more-than-a-million-people-to-mastodon-but-many-arent-sticking-around |website=The Guardian |date=7 January 2023 |access-date=9 January 2023}}</ref> On 19 March 2023, Mastodon passed the ten million user mark.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.itworldcanada.com/article/mastodon-passes-the-10-million-account-milestone/533720 | title=Mastodon passes the 10 million account milestone &#124; IT World Canada News | date=20 March 2023 }}</ref>

===Forks===
In 2017, [[Pixiv]] launched a Mastodon-based social network named Pawoo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pawoo.net/about/more|title=Mastodon hosted on pawoo.net|website=Pawoo|language=en|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref> The service was acquired by media company Russell in 2019. Pawoo is banned by most instances on Mastodon due to allowing {{transl|ja|[[lolicon]]}} art.<ref>{{cite news | first1=April | last1=Glaser | first2=Will | last2=Oremus | url=https://slate.com/technology/2018/08/mastodon-what-you-need-to-know-about-the-new-social-network-competing-with-twitter.html | title=The New Social Network Dodging Government Surveillance—and Nazis | work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] | date=2018-08-30 | accessdate=2022-04-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | first=Ethan | last=Zuckerman | authorlink=Ethan Zuckerman | url=https://ethanzuckerman.com/2017/08/18/mastodon-is-big-in-japan-the-reason-why-is-uncomfortable | title=Mastodon is big in Japan. The reason why is… uncomfortable | date=2018-08-18 | accessdate=2022-04-27}}</ref>

In April 2019, computer manufacturer [[Purism (company)|Purism]] released a fork of Mastodon named Librem Social.<ref>{{cite magazine|access-date=2019-07-17|title=Purism Launches Librem One, a Suite of Privacy-Protecting, No-Track, No-Ad Apps and Services|url=https://www.linuxjournal.com/content/purism-launches-librem-one-suite-privacy-protecting-no-track-no-ad-apps-and-services|magazine=[[Linux Journal]]|first=Bryan|last=Lunduke|date=30 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|access-date=2019-07-17|title=Librem One: Purism startet Angebot für sichere Online-Dienste|language=de|trans-title=Purism Launches Secure Online Services Offering|url=https://www.golem.de/news/librem-one-purism-startet-angebot-fuer-sichere-online-dienste-1905-141007.html|website={{ill|Golem.de|de}}|date=2 May 2019|first1=Kristian|last1=Kißling|author2=Linux Magazin|first3=Sebastian|last3=Grüner|author2-link=Linux Magazin}}</ref>

[[Gab (social network)|Gab]], a controversial social network with a [[Far-right politics|far-right]] user base, changed its software platform to a fork of Mastodon and became the largest Mastodon node in July 2019.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Ben|last1=Makuch|first2=Jason|last2=Koebler|first3=Derek|last3=Mead|access-date=2019-07-17|title=Mastodon Was Designed to Be a Nazi-Free Twitter—Now It's the Exact Opposite|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/mb8y3x/the-nazi-free-alternative-to-twitter-is-now-home-to-the-biggest-far-right-social-network|date=11 July 2019|website=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]}}</ref> Gab's adoption of Mastodon allowed Gab to be accessed from third-party Mastodon applications, although four of them blocked Gab shortly after the change.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Adi|last1=Robertson|access-date=2019-07-17|title=How the biggest decentralized social network is dealing with its Nazi problem|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/7/12/20691957/mastodon-decentralized-social-network-gab-migration-fediverse-app-blocking|date=12 July 2019|website=[[The Verge]]}}</ref> In response, Mastodon's main contributors stated in their blog that they were "completely opposed to Gab’s project and philosophy", and criticized Gab for attempting "to monetize and platform [[racist]] content while hiding behind the banner of free speech" and for "[[paywall]]ing basic features that are freely available on Mastodon".<ref>{{cite web|access-date=2019-07-17|title=Statement on Gab's fork of Mastodon|url=http://blog.joinmastodon.org/2019/07/statement-on-gabs-fork-of-mastodon/|website=Official Mastodon Blog|author=Eleanor|date=4 July 2019}}</ref>

In October 2019, the [[Fourth Estate Public Benefit Corporation]] released a fork of Mastodon named Civiq.Social.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fourthestate.org/news/announcing-the-launch-of-civiq/|title=Announcing the launch of Project Civiq|date=24 October 2019|website=Fourth Estate|access-date=24 October 2019}}</ref>

''Tooter'' is an Indian [[social networking]] product launched in September 2020. Tooter is forked (derived) from the main branch of Mastodon software.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.arre.co.in/technology/how-swadeshi-is-tooter-if-it-clones-far-right-platforms-like-gab/amp/?__twitter_impression=true | title=How "Swadeshi" is Tooter If It Clones Far-Right Platforms Like Gab? | publisher=arre.co.in | date=27 November 2020 | access-date=19 December 2020 }}</ref>

In October 2021, former US President [[Donald Trump]] founded [[Truth Social]], which is based on Mastodon. Initially, Truth Social did not make its [[source code]] available, violating Mastodon's [[AGPLv3]] license. Eugen Rochko sent a formal letter to Truth Social's chief legal officer on 26 October 2021.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rochko |first1=Eugen |title=Trump's new social media platform found using Mastodon code |url=https://blog.joinmastodon.org/2021/10/trumps-new-social-media-platform-found-using-mastodon-code/ |website=Mastodon Blog |date=October 29, 2021}}</ref> On 12 November 2021, Truth Social published its source code.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kan |first1=Michael |title=Trump's Social Media Site Quietly Admits It's Based on Mastodon |url=https://uk.pcmag.com/social-media/137421/trumps-social-media-site-quietly-admits-its-based-on-mastodon |website=[[PCMag]] |date=December 1, 2021}}</ref>

== Security ==
{{One source section|date=May 2023}}
While Mastodon's decentralized structure is one of its most distinctive features, it also poses additional security challenges.

Since many Mastodon instances are run by volunteers, some security experts are concerned about data security and responsiveness to new threats (like high-severity vulnerabilities) considering the difficulty of configuring and maintaining servers as well as uneven skill level among administrators. Errors in instance configuration and security bugs in server implementation has already led to user data being scraped or changed by attackers. It is worth noting that Mastodon collects considerably less personal data, compared to other social media platforms which makes it a lower-value target and potential losses less significant.<ref name=":4">{{Cite web |last=Goodin |first=Dan |date=2022-11-29 |title=How secure a Twitter replacement is Mastodon? Let us count the ways |url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2022/11/how-secure-a-twitter-replacement-is-mastodon-let-us-count-the-ways/ |access-date=2023-01-28 |website=[[Ars Technica]] |language=en-us}}</ref>

Volunteer-run instances may not have resources to deal with DDoS attacks the same way the centralized platforms do. This susceptibility could potentially be used as a way to silence political voices.<ref name=":4" />

Eugen Rochko argues that these issues do not set it apart from other software products that can be hosted by non-professionals.

{{As of|2022|November}}, Mastodon server has not yet undergone any formal security audit and security weaknesses are likely to be discovered in the future.<ref name=":4" />

Another issue can be content moderation. While Mastodon instances can limit or filter out undesirable types of content, a large-scale harassment and misinformation campaign may require active moderation.<ref name=":4" />

==Funding==
Mastodon is [[crowdfunded]] and does not contain ads; as of November 2022, it was supported by 3,500 people. Since 2021 it has been registered in Germany as a [[nonprofit organization]] ({{lang-de|gemeinnützige [[GmbH]]}}).<ref>{{Cite news| last=Glanz |first=Berit |title=Twitter-Alternative: Wer steckt eigentlich hinter Mastodon? |language=de |work=FAZ.NET |url=https://www.faz.net/aktuell/feuilleton/medien/twitter-alternative-mastodon-wer-steckt-hinter-der-plattform-18450637.html |access-date=2022-11-14 |issn=0174-4909}}</ref>

